[
    {
        "content": "<p>Does every elementary topos admit a faithful functor to the category of sets?</p>\n<p>This is the case for every Grothendieck topos, and also for the few examples of non-Grothendieck toposes that I know (like the topos of finite sets or the topos of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span>-sets where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> is a \"large\" category with one object).</p>\n<p>Maybe there are even elementary toposes that are not locally small?</p>",
        "id": 215294605,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1604308594
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the category of <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/small+presheaf\">small</a> sheaves on a site (probably we need the site to have finite limits) is supposed to be an elementary topos, and it doesn't seem obviously concretizable, so maybe that would be a place to look.</p>",
        "id": 215310686,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1604319614
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"282722\">Jens Hemelaer</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/230087-theory.3A-topos.20theory/topic/Every.20elementary.20topos.20concretizable.3F/near/215294605\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This is the case for every Grothendieck topos.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>What functor are you referring to here? A functor represented by some \"bound\" (separating object) for the topos?<br>\nAn unbounded topos over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68611em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">t</span></span></span></span></span> does seem like the way to go.</p>",
        "id": 215313299,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1604321221
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(does a single separating object always exist if the topos is bounded? That seems like a very strong result, since it would surely imply that every topos is a subtopos of a topos of actions of a monoid)</p>",
        "id": 215313472,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1604321318
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can equip the category of presheaves on any small category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> with the faithful functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mo>∐</mo><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow></msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>−</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\coprod_{a \\in A} \\mathrm{Hom}(a, -)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.07708em;vertical-align:-0.32708000000000004em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:-0.0000050000000000050004em;\">∐</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.17862099999999992em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.40029em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">a</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">∈</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">A</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.32708000000000004em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">H</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">m</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> to Set.</p>",
        "id": 215314055,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1604321631
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So to be concretizable it's enough to have a small dense (full) subcategory, which every Grothendieck topos does.</p>",
        "id": 215314246,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1604321713
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, so that's true for any locally small category with a separating set of objects.</p>",
        "id": 215314265,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1604321724
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276480\">Reid Barton</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/230087-theory.3A-topos.20theory/topic/Every.20elementary.20topos.20concretizable.3F/near/215310686\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think the category of <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/small+presheaf\">small</a> sheaves on a site (probably we need the site to have finite limits) is supposed to be an elementary topos, and it doesn't seem obviously concretizable, so maybe that would be a place to look.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Thanks! So maybe an example is the category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mo>∏</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow></msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">s</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\prod_{i \\in I} \\mathbf{Sets}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.07708em;vertical-align:-0.32708000000000004em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:-0.0000050000000000050004em;\">∏</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.17862099999999992em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.40029em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">∈</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.32708000000000004em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">s</span></span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> is some proper class? It seems that the subobject classifier, exponential objects and finite limits can be defined pointwise here.</p>\n<p>There seem to be some size issues here: if you work in von Neumann--Bernays--Gödel set theory, then maybe the collection of objects in the category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mo>∏</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow></msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">s</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\prod_{i \\in I} \\mathbf{Sets}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.07708em;vertical-align:-0.32708000000000004em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:-0.0000050000000000050004em;\">∏</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.17862099999999992em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.40029em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">∈</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.32708000000000004em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">s</span></span></span></span></span> can fail to form a 'class'. But this problem appears also for the category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span>-sets where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> is a large monoid, I think.</p>",
        "id": 215323443,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1604326592
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As soon as you have a topos which fails to be locally small with respect to some fixed universe of Sets, like in your example, it certainly can't be concrete in a faithful way, but I had hoped there would be a more concrete example of a locally small topos over Set that failed to be bounded. Or is local smallness (i.e. Set-enrichment) the same as being faithfully concretizable?</p>",
        "id": 215324912,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1604327282
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Regarding your last question: the category of topological spaces and homotopy classes of maps between them is locally small but not concretizable (see <a href=\"https://amathew.wordpress.com/2012/01/26/homotopy-is-not-concrete/\">here</a>). If I recall correctly, another example is the category of small categories and functors up to natural equivalence.</p>",
        "id": 215327302,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1604328318
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's a relief...! So there should be some locally small but not concrete topos, I expect.</p>",
        "id": 215328983,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1604329104
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not sure whether the product of a class-sized family of copies of Set really makes sense at all in ZFC, but it's definitely not locally small, as Morgan said. That's why I suggested working with small (pre)sheaves, which we can regard as formal small colimits of representables. They form an ordinary, class-sized locally small category which is however not locally presentable.</p>",
        "id": 215330593,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1604329777
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not sure exactly when the category of small presheaves on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> is an elementary a topos. At a minimum it has to have finite limits, which is a nontrivial condition on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>. For example if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> is a class-sized discrete category then the terminal object of the presheaf category is not a small presheaf.</p>",
        "id": 215330824,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1604329872
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the condition on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> is that every finite diagram has a set of weakly universal cones (i.e., a set of cones such that every cone factors through one of them in at least one way). For example, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> could itself have finite limits.</p>",
        "id": 215331462,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1604330101
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The rest of the Giraud axioms seem fine (the category of presheaves on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> in a bigger universe is definitely a topos, and things like small coproducts and coequalizers and pullbacks don't leave the full subcategory of small presheaves) so I guess the above condition on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> is enough for the presheaf category to be an elementary topos.</p>",
        "id": 215331649,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1604330168
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I also don't know when exactly the small sheaves for a topology on such <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> form what we could call a \"Giraud topos\" (= Giraud axioms minus a set of generators), but I understand that it's supposed to be true for condensed sets, for example.</p>",
        "id": 215332515,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1604330539
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, I misunderstood what small presheaves are. Thank you!</p>",
        "id": 215333176,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1604330826
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A Giraud topos is a cocomplete locally small pretopos, no? This is rather easy to arrange, and we can do better. Say <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>R</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msup><mo>→</mo><mi>T</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi><mi>o</mi><msub><mi>s</mi><mi>b</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R^{op} \\to Topos_b</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">o</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.33610799999999996em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">b</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is a cofiltered diagram with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> well-founded (maybe we don't need this bit). Then the colimit of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>T</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi><mi>o</mi><msubsup><mi>s</mi><mi>b</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msubsup><mo>→</mo><mi>L</mi><mi>E</mi><msub><mi>X</mi><mrow><mi>c</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>c</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R\\to Topos_b^{op} \\to LEX_{cocont}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.083608em;vertical-align:-0.3013079999999999em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">o</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7823em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.3986920000000005em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">b</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.1809080000000005em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3013079999999999em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2805559999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.07847em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">t</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> (lextensive categories with finite-limit- and colimit-preserving functors) is a cocomplete Heyting pretopos with a subobject classifier and finitary W-types. It might not be locally small, but if the diagram of inverse image functors is <em>eventually full</em> it will be. Further, if powerobjects are eventually constant, it will be an unbounded Set-topos.</p>",
